{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bf4babf7-756b-48c4-a7b7-746f717860f6","content":"Three breaking changes in EF Core 10 hit your scenario directly:\n\n---\n\n### 1. JSON columns default to `nvarchar(4000)` instead of `nvarchar(max)`\n\nWith `UseAzureSql()` in EF Core 10, primitive collections (`string[] Tags`) and owned types mapped via `ToJson()` default to `nvarchar(4000)`. Your next migration will generate `AlterColumn` operations that shrink every JSON column — risking **silent data truncation** if any row exceeds 4000 chars.\n\n**Fix** — explicitly pin the max length:\n```csharp\n// Primitive collection\nb.Property(e => e.Tags).HasColumnType(\"nvarchar(max)\");\n\n// Owned type mapped to JSON\nb.OwnsOne(e => e.Address, ob =>\n{\n    ob.ToJson();\n    ob.HasColumnType(\"nvarchar(max)\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `Contains()` over `List<int>` — OPENJSON now emits an explicit `WITH` clause\n\nEF Core 9 generated **untyped** OPENJSON:\n```sql\nWHERE x.Id IN (SELECT [value] FROM OPENJSON(@p))\n```\n\nEF Core 10 generates **typed** OPENJSON:\n```sql\nWHERE x.Id IN (SELECT [value] FROM OPENJSON(@p) WITH ([value] int '$'))\n```\n\nImpact:\n- **Query plans change** — cached plans in Query Store / plan guides won't match.\n- The implicit `nvarchar → int` conversion that hurt index seeks is **eliminated**, so most queries get faster. But plans that accidentally relied on the scan behavior may regress.\n- If you had workarounds (e.g., `EF.Functions.OpenJson`) to force typed parsing, they may now double-wrap or conflict.\n\n**Fix** — rebaseline query-plan monitoring after upgrade and remove manual `OPENJSON` workarounds.\n\n---\n\n### 3. `dotnet ef migrations add` without `--framework` on a multi-target project\n\nWhen the project targets `net9.0;net10.0`, the EF tools pick the **highest TFM** (net10.0) by default. That means:\n\n- The migration snapshot is generated with EF Core 10 conventions (e.g., `nvarchar(4000)` defaults).\n- Running the app on `net9.0` (EF Core 9) sees a snapshot it doesn't understand, producing **model-diff errors or spurious \"pending changes\" warnings**.\n\n**Fix** — always specify the framework explicitly:\n```bash\ndotnet ef migrations add MyMigration --framework net10.0\n```\nAnd ensure migrations are generated and applied against a single, pinned TFM. If you share the migration assembly across both targets, conditionally compile or keep separate migration folders.\n\n---\n\n### Quick checklist\n\n| Area | Action |\n|---|---|\n| JSON columns | Audit all primitive collections & `ToJson()` owned types; add `.HasColumnType(\"nvarchar(max)\")` where needed |\n| `Contains()` queries | Re-test query perf; drop manual OPENJSON workarounds |\n| Multi-target migrations | Add `--framework net10.0` to all `dotnet ef` commands in CI and docs |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a0cc2b98-f252-4daf-a807-bb5551b770d3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about EF Core 10 breaking changes that affect their specific scenario. Let me analyze their three concerns:\n\n1. Primitive collections (string[] Tags) and owned types mapped to JSON columns (currently nvarchar(max)) with UseAzureSql\n2. .Contains() on List<int> in LINQ queries that currently use OPENJSON\n3. Multi-targeting net9.0 and net10.0 with `dotnet ef migrations add` without --framework\n\nLet me address each of these based on my knowledge of EF Core 10 breaking changes.\n\n**1. JSON columns changing from nvarchar(max) to nvarchar(4000)**\n\n\nIn EF Core 10 with Azure SQL, primitive collections and owned types stored as JSON now default to `nvarchar(4000)` instead of `nvarchar(max)`, which can cause data truncation if your JSON exceeds that limit. You'll need to explicitly configure `.HasMaxLength()` or `.HasColumnType(\"nvarchar(max)\")` to preserve the larger column size.\n\nActually, I should clarify what I'm certain about regarding EF Core 10 breaking changes. There are shifts in how query translation works—particularly