 which could lose data in migrations. For `.Contains()` on collections, EF Core 10 generates `OPENJSON` with explicit type casting rather than untyped calls, potentially breaking existing query plans and hints. I'm trying to pin down exactly what changed between EF Core 8 and 9 versus 10 to give you the most accurate breaking changes. With `UseAzureSql()` in EF Core 10, JSON columns for primitive collections and owned types now default to `nvarchar(4000)` instead of `nvarchar(max)`, which can cause data loss if your JSON exceeds that limit. I'd need to explicitly set the column type to `nvarchar(max)` to preserve existing behavior. Now I'm looking at how the `Contains()` method translates differently in EF Core 10.\n\nThe SQL generation for `.Contains()` on parameterized lists has shifted from an untyped OPENJSON to a typed version with explicit column definitions, or potentially a different translation altogether. This change impacts query plan caching, index usage, and any query store hints I might be relying on.\n\nThere's also a tooling change: when multi-targeting projects with both net9.0 and net10.0, I need to explicitly specify `--framework` when running `dotnet ef migrations add`, otherwise the CLI defaults to the highest target framework and applies EF Core 10 conventions. For Azure SQL specifically, `.Contains()` gets translated differently, and EF Core 10's Azure SQL provider now uses parameterized JSON with typed OPENJSON for collection parameters instead of the untyped version—this enables better index usage but changes existing query plans. I'm also thinking through whether there's a specific breaking change around `dotnet ef` and multi-targeting in EF Core 10, particularly around how the design-time services select the target framework when multiple are available.\n\nThe real issue seems to be that when the tools auto-select net10.0 as the highest target framework, the generated migration snapshot uses new conventions like the nvarchar(4000) default, which then causes problems when the app runs on net9.0 with EF Core 9—so pinning the `--framework` flag is essential to avoid accidentally mixing migration conventions across versions.","outputTokens":4009,"requestId":"0400:A6C81:4636D3:50ED62:6A051F03"},"id":"669f8159-6280-473c-b239-c6f040882367","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:03:09.439Z","parentId":"4c8d685c-8c6a-4b11-8295-83f4e2f54af4"}
